First, draw a sketch. We can label the \(C\) axis by adding integer multiples of 150 to 480. We know to shade the left because low values of \(C\) satisfy the condition \(C<c\) (regardless of the exact value of \(c\)). We donâ€™t know exactly where to place the boundary, but we know the left area is 0.27.

It is helpful to know the following approximations:

\(z\) \(P(Z<z)\)
-3 0.001
-2 0.023
-1 0.159
0 0.5
1 0.841
2 0.977
3 0.999

So, we know the \(z\)-score is between -1 and 0. Remember, \(Z\) and \(z\) always refer to the standard normal variable.


By using the \(z\) table we can determine \(z\) more precisely.

\(z\) \(P(Z<z)\)
-0.64 0.2611
-0.63 0.2643
-0.62 0.2676
-0.61 0.2709
-0.6 0.2743
-0.63 0.2776

Either -0.62 or -0.61 is a good estimation of \(z\), and either value will lead you to an acceptable answer. Using other tools, a more accurate value can be found. I will show the work with a more accurate value. \[z=-0.6128\]

We now convert the \(z\) score into a \(c\) score. \[\begin{aligned} c &= \mu+z\sigma \\ &= 480+(-0.6128)(150) \\ &= 388.1 \end{aligned}\]

We can also visualize this with a spinner.


The tolerance for an acceptable answer was \(\pm 10\) from 388.0780513. So, anything between 378.0780513 and 398.0780513 was accepted.
